If you're someone like me who still likes to use semi colons add this to your .eslintrc.js file that gets added your src folder in the server folder. 

module.exports = {
    "extends": "standard",
    "rules": {
        "semi": [0, "always"]  //setting the first index to 0 is what turns the rule off.
    }
}; 

No more pesky semi colon errors. Or if eslint is driving you insane you can do this instead: 

 "scripts": {
    "start": "nodemon src/app.js",
    "seed": "node seed"
  }.

Now it won't stop the server, because it's no longer being run.

